StoreMarket_hist <- ManagerDatabyYear %>% 
  distinct(Year, Unit, StoreMarket) %>% 
  arrange(Year, Unit)

RestaurantPerformanceInfo_used <- 
RestaurantPerformanceInfo %>% 
  left_join(y = StoreMarket_hist, by = c("Year" = "Year", "UnitID" = "Unit")) %>% 
  mutate(ReturnOnLabour = round((Profit / Payroll), digits = 4))

RestaurantPerformanceInfo_used %>% 
  select(UnitID, Year, StoreMarket, ReturnOnLabour) %>% 
  group_by(Year, StoreMarket) %>% 
  summarise(Mean = mean(ReturnOnLabour),
            Std_Dev = sd(ReturnOnLabour),
            Min = min(ReturnOnLabour),
            Max = max(ReturnOnLabour),
            Range = Max - Min) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  bind_rows(
    RestaurantPerformanceInfo_used %>% 
      group_by(Year) %>% 
      summarize(StoreMarket = "Overall",
                Mean = mean(ReturnOnLabour),
                Std_Dev = sd(ReturnOnLabour),
                Min = min(ReturnOnLabour),
                Max = max(ReturnOnLabour),
                Range = Max - Min) %>% 
      ungroup()
    ) %>% 
  arrange(Year, StoreMarket) %>% 
  gt()

set.seed(123)

build_lr_regression <- function(data, dependent_var){
  lm_formula <- str_c(dependent_var, " ~ ", ".")
  
  fitted_model <- 
    linear_reg() %>% 
    set_engine("lm") %>% 
    set_mode("regression") %>% 
    fit(as.formula(lm_formula), data = data)
  
  lr_training_pred <- predict(fitted_model, data)
  data_w_pred <- bind_cols(data, lr_training_pred)
  
  lr_reg_metrics <- metric_set(rmse, rsq, mae)
  lr_performance <- lr_reg_metrics(data_w_pred, truth = !!sym(dependent_var), estimate = .pred)
  
  output <- list(#model_summary = fitted_model, commented out because generally not useful, and mess up html output
                 model_parameters = gt(tidy(fitted_model)),
                 data_preview = gt(head(data_w_pred, 10)),
                 metrics = gt(lr_performance), 
                 number_observations = gt(tibble(Num_obs = as.character(data %>% nrow(.)))))
  return(output)
}

# can't use mger performance data from Q3 even though all sales and sales change have been done, there are some years some stores don;t have performance rating info, which reduces fidelity of data. Restaurant performance doesn't have this problem.

RestaurantPerformanceInfo_wTurnover <- RestaurantPerformanceInfo %>% 
  inner_join(y = UnitTurnover, by = c("UnitID" = "Unit", "Year" = "Year")) %>%

Conclusions:

  • Best performing model for the past year sales is: Sales ~ TurnoverChange + SalesLastYear (highest Rsq with lowest error metrics, than the manager performance rating based models)
  • Every 1% increase in turnoverrate change, sales decreases by $10K.
  • Generally, turover based models are better performing than management performing models.
  • Looking at static unitturnoverrate, model Sales ~ UnitTurnoverPerc + SalesLastYear also performs well, though slightly worse than turnoverratechange
  • In that model, if turnoverrate increases by 1%, then the unit store sales decreases by about $2600.
  • Therefore, reducing turnover not only reduce hiring/rehiring costs but also contributes to sales performance.

Room for improvement: - We haven’t included for all years to, so it just works for the most recent year.

Looking at the p-value, it essentially negates the necessity to include UnitTurnoverPerc as part of the model.

A rerun of the model excluding the UnitTurnoverPerc gives pretty much the same effective model.

Logistic Regression - Unit Sales, Store Market, Prior Year Unit Sales, Nonexempt Group Mean Ave EngagementScore (2022)

Code 
set.seed(123)
build_lgr_model <- function(data, dependent_var) {
  # commented out, we will only do a single sample logistic regression for diagnositcs
  # splits <- initial_split(data, prop = 0.8, strata = HiringDecision)
  # AM_hire_train <- training(splits)
  # AM_hire_test <- testing(splits)
  
  lgr_formula <- as.formula(str_c(dependent_var, " ~ ", "."))
  
  fitted_model <- 
    logistic_reg() %>% 
    set_engine("glm") %>% 
    set_mode("classification") %>% 
    fit(lgr_formula, family = "binomial", data = data)
  
  lr_training_pred <- bind_cols(predict(fitted_model, data), 
                                predict(fitted_model, data, type = "prob"), 
                                data %>% select(!!sym(dependent_var))) 
    
  roc_auc_score <- lr_training_pred %>% 
    roc_auc(truth = !!sym(dependent_var), .pred_Yes, event_level = "first")
  
  accuracy_score <- lr_training_pred %>% 
    accuracy(truth = !!sym(dependent_var), .pred_class)
  
  performance_table <- bind_rows(roc_auc_score, accuracy_score)
    
  
  output_list <- list(model = fitted_model,
                      estimators = gt(tidy(fitted_model, exponentiate = TRUE)),
                      prediction = gt(head(lr_training_pred),10),
                      performance = gt(performance_table),
                      NumObservations = gt(tibble(NumObservation = nrow(data))))
  
  return(output_list)
}

ManagerTurnoverPredictData <- ManagerDatabyYear_wPayChange %>% 
   mutate(Turnover = relevel(as.factor(Turnover), ref = "Yes"),
          Race = relevel(as.factor(Race), ref = "URM"),
          Gender = relevel(as.factor(Gender), ref = "Female"),
          StoreMarket = relevel(as.factor(StoreMarket), ref = "Large"),
          JobTitle = relevel(as.factor(JobTitle), ref = "Manager"),
          WageRate1000 = WageRate/1000, 
          WageRateChange1000 = WageRateChange/1000) %>% 
    select(Turnover, Race, Gender, StoreMarket, JobTitle, WageRateChange1000, WageRate1000, PerformanceLastYear) %>% 
    filter(!is.na(WageRateChange1000))

lgr_turnover <- build_lgr_model(data = ManagerTurnoverPredictData, dependent_var = "Turnover")

Conclusion:

  • Wage and particularly wage increase are vital to keep managers from leaving. with $1000 wage increase from year to year, it decreases the likelihood of turnover by almost 7 fold.

  • Higher previous performance rating seems to contribute higher likelihood of leaving.

  • Demongraphics don’t seem contribute likelihood of turnover. Gender is non-contributing factor.

  • Medium market stores seem to less likelihood of churning

  • Being Manager seems to reduce likelihood of churning

Propensity to leave (2023)

Potential problems with this prediction:

  • we have to assume the wage increase will keep as it is. (i.e. from 2021 to 2022)
  • can we remove wage rate change? people who join us this year won’t have this data. Assistant managers may get overlooked, their tenure is only 1.3 years.

Overall, it seems that propensity to leave is about 13.6% chance to leave, in the next year.

Code 
MgmtTurnoverPredData <- 
  CurrentEmployees %>% 
      filter(`Exempt/Non-Exempt` == "Exempt") %>% 
     mutate(Race = relevel(as.factor(Race), ref = "URM"),
            Gender = relevel(as.factor(Gender), ref = "Female"),
            StoreMarket = relevel(as.factor(StoreMarket), ref = "Large"),
            JobTitle = relevel(as.factor(JobTitle), ref = "Manager"),
            WageRate1000 = WageRate2022/1000, 
            # it also seems that we have to assume the wage increase will keep as it is.
            WageRateChange1000 = (WageRate2022 - WageRate2021)/1000) %>% 
      # can we remove wage rate change? people who join us this year won't have this data. Assistant managers may get overlooked, their tenure is only 1.3 years
      filter(!is.na(WageRateChange1000)) %>% 
      select(Race, Gender, StoreMarket, JobTitle, WageRateChange1000, WageRate1000, PerformanceRating2022, Unit, ID) %>% 
      #this is to trick the model into believing we are passing the Performance last year data in, but when we make the prediction, we need current year's performance.
      rename(PerformanceLastYear = PerformanceRating2022)
      
MgmtTrunoverPredicted <- 
  MgmtTurnoverPredData %>% 
    bind_cols(., predict(lgr_turnover$model, ., type = "prob")) %>% 
    rename(PropensitytoLeave = .pred_Yes,
           PropensitytoStay = .pred_No)

#some NAs exist because new hires don't have any performance rating yet, those are removed
MgmtTrunoverPredicted %>% 
  summarise(AvePropensitytoLeave = mean(PropensitytoLeave, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  gt()
